Rating: 3
I made two au gratins for an Easter feast, this one and one with goat cheese. For this one, I just scrubbed the potatoes well and left the skins on. I used a good, sharp yellow cheddar because I wanted the color, and I understand that the color has nothing to do with the taste. Finally, I added a handful of chopped, sauted pancetta for a little extra taste. Baked half-way, covered, earlier in the day. Refrigerated. Then finished off uncovered just before dinner. I personally liked the goat cheese one better, but there was less of this one left over at the end of the night. Don't worry if it looks a little curdled before removing the foil, all that bakes off and browns up during the second portion of baking. Run under the broiler for a minute or two if you have to.

